USER: What is the difference between a stack and a queue in C++?

ASSISTANT: In C++, a stack and a queue are both container classes that store elements in a specific order. The main difference between them is the order in which elements are added and removed.

A stack is a last-in-first-out (LIFO) data structure. This means that the last element added to the stack will be the first one to be removed. Elements are added to the top of the stack using the push() function, and removed from the top of the stack using the pop() function.

A queue, on the other hand, is a first-in-first-out (FIFO) data structure. This means that the first element added to the queue will be the first one to be removed. Elements are added to the back of the queue using the push() function, and removed from the front of the queue using the pop() function.

In summary, the main difference between a stack and a queue in C++ is the order in which elements are added and removed. Stacks are LIFO and queues are FIFO. <|endoftext|>

