USER: What is overloading in C++? How is it different from overriding?

ASSISTANT: Overloading is a feature in C++ that allows you to define multiple functions with the same name but different parameters. When you call an overloaded function, the compiler determines which version of the function to use based on the types and number of arguments passed to it.

Overriding, on the other hand, is the process of providing a different implementation of a virtual function in a derived class. When you call a virtual function on an object, the runtime system determines which version of the function to use based on the actual type of the object, rather than the declared type of the pointer or reference that points to it.

In other words, overloading is used to define multiple functions with the same name but different signatures, while overriding is used to provide a new implementation of a virtual function in a derived class.

One important difference between overloading and overriding is that overloading is resolved at compile time, while overriding is resolved at runtime. This means that when you call an overloaded function, the compiler knows which version of the function to use before the program is run. When you call an overridden function, however, the actual type of the object is not known until the program is run, so the decision about which version of the function to use cannot be made until then.

Another difference is that overloading can be done for both member and non-member functions, while overriding only applies to virtual member functions.

Overall, overloading and overriding are both useful features in C++ that allow you to write more flexible and expressive code, but they serve different purposes and should be used appropriately depending on the problem you're trying to solve. <|endoftext|>

